3) Why I chose Boston and rejected Out of the Blue:
- Boston (debut) is a tightly produced, album-oriented rock record known for its very polished studio production (Tom Scholz’s engineering and arrangements), distinctive guitar tones, and strong, memorable hooks—most famously the single "More Than a Feeling." Those attributes make it an immediately rewarding and repeatedly enjoyable CD listening experience: concise track lengths, consistent tonal palette across the album, and a production style that translates well to CD playback (clarity, punch in the midrange and guitars). For a listener whose primary stated preference is simply enjoying CDs, an album that consistently delivers immediate musical payoff and high studio polish is a strong fit.
- Out of the Blue (Electric Light Orchestra) is also a well-regarded, popular record and contains enduring tracks such as "Mr. Blue Sky." However, it is a sprawling double album with elaborate orchestral arrangements and progressive pop/rock ambitions. That breadth and complexity make it an excellent artistic statement, but it can be a less focused single-session listening experience compared with Boston’s tighter AOR approach. For a general CD enthusiast without a stated preference for long-form, progressive/orchestral pop, the double-album scope and greater stylistic variety of Out of the Blue make it less directly aligned with the straightforward, repeatable listening pleasure implied by the sole expressed preference.
In short: given only the clear preference of enjoying CDs and no specified genre likes/dislikes, Boston’s concentrated, highly produced, and hook-driven album is the better match for a listener who wants an immediately rewarding and sonically consistent CD experience; Out of the Blue is excellent but its double-album, orchestral-progressive nature makes it a less ideal single-choice for that specific, broad enjoyment criterion.

