- Back in Black, by contrast, pulls most of its strengths into the rhythmic and riff domain: attack‑first guitars, locked/punchy low end and riff sequencing. Those are explicit negatives in my self‑introduction: I dislike mixes that prioritize rhythm and attack at the expense of breath and nuance, and I prefer vocals that sit forward but breathe rather than being locked to the rhythm. While Back in Black’s mastering and warmth are attractive, its fundamental mix philosophy (drums/guitars driving and dominating the sonic foreground) conflicts with the essential album‑centric, vocal‑forward, restrained‑arrangement aesthetic I prize.
- In short, despite the singles‑collection caveat, the 1962–1966 set better preserves the specific elements I value most — tactile, front‑and‑center but breathing vocals, close harmonies, midrange warmth, clear separation and restrained overdubbing — whereas Back in Black emphasizes attack and rhythm in ways that run counter to my stated dislikes. Therefore I select the singles collection.

